The '''nelicourvi weaver''' ('''''Ploceus nelicourvi''''') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Ploceidae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Madagascar]]. Together with its closest relative, the [[sakalava weaver]], it is sometimes placed in a separate genus ''Nelicurvius''. A slender, sparrow-like bird, it is {{convert|15|cm|in|abbr=on}} long and weighing {{convert|20–28|g|oz|abbr=on}}. Breeding males have a black bill and head, brown eyes, yellow collar, grey belly, chestnut-brown lower tail coverts, olive back, and blackish flight feathers edged greenish. Non-breeding males have mottled grey and green heads. In the breeding female the front of the head is yellow and the back olive green, with a broad yellow eyebrow. It builds solitary, roofed, retort-shaped nests, hanging by a rope from a branch, vine or bamboo stem, in an open space. It primarily feeds on insects, looking on its own or in very small groups, often together with [[long-billed bernieria]]. Its natural [[habitat]] is subtropical or tropical moist lowland and mountain [[forest]]s. The [[conservation status]] of Nelicourvi weaver is [[least concern]] according to the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name="iucn status 12 November 2021" />

== Taxonomy ==
The nelicourvi weaver was first [[species description|described]] by Italian naturalist and physician [[Giovanni Antonio Scopoli]] in 1786, who called it ''Parvus nelicourvi''. The description was based on a specimen that [[Pierre Sonnerat]], a French naturalist and explorer, had collected during his 1770 visit of Madagascar, on the eastern coast, possibly near Fort Dauphin.<ref name=WW>{{cite web|website= Weaver Watch|title= Nelicourvi Weaver Ploceus nelicourvi|url= http://weavers.adu.org.za/sp.php?spp=3924#|access-date= 2017-06-10}}</ref> In 1789, [[Johann Friedrich Gmelin]], a naturalist from Germany, gave the name ''Loxia pensilis'', based on a description by English ornithologist [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]], who himself had not provided a [[binomial name]].<ref>{{cite web|website= AnimalBase|title= Species taxon summary pensilis Gmelin, 1789 described in Loxia|url= http://www.animalbase.uni-goettingen.de/zooweb/servlet/AnimalBase/home/speciestaxon?id=46416|access-date= 2017-06-13}}</ref> In 1827, George Shaw, an English zoologist and botanist, included ''L. pensilis'' in the genus ''Ploceus''.<ref>{{cite book|first= George|last= Shaw|title= General zoology or systematic natural history|publisher= Kearsley|year= 1826|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=dIkUAAAAQAAJ&q=General+zoology+or+systematic+natural+history&pg=PP1|access-date= 2017-06-13}}</ref> In 1850, [[Charles Lucien Bonaparte]] assigned the species to his newly erected genus ''Nelicurvius''. No subspecies have been described.<ref name=Phyl>{{cite journal|first1= Thilina N.|last1= De Silva|first2= A. Townsend|last2= Peterson|first3= John M.|last3= Bates|first4= Sumudu W.|last4= Fernandoa|first5= Matthew G.|last5= Girard|year= 2017|title= Phylogenetic relationships of weaverbirds (Aves: Ploceidae): A first robust phylogeny based on mitochondrial and nuclear markers|journal= Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume= 109|pages= 21–32|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2016.12.013|pmid= 28012957|bibcode= 2017MolPE.109...21D|s2cid= 205841906}}</ref> The original genus name ''Parvus'' is Latin and means "little". It is presumed that the species [[epithet]] ''nelicourvi'' was derived from the [[Tamil language|Tamil]] word "nellukuruvi", a name for a [[waxbill]] or finch on Sri Lanka. In 1783, [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] gave the species its first common name in English, calling it "pensile grosbeak".<ref name=WW /> "Nelicourvi weaver" has been designated the official name by the [[International Ornithological Committee]] (IOC).<ref name="ioclist">{{cite web|editor1-last= Gill|editor1-first= Frank|editor1-link= Frank Gill (ornithologist)|editor2-last= Donsker|editor2-first= David|year= 2017|title= Old World sparrows, snowfinches & weavers|work= World Bird List Version 7.1|url= http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/weavers/|publisher= International Ornithologists' Union|access-date= 16 April 2017}}</ref> Vernacular names in [[Malagasy language|Malagasi]] are  ''fodisaina'', ''fodifetsy'' and ''farifotramavo''.<ref>{{cite web|website= Avibase|title= Nelicourvi weaver|url= http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=263E6762EE3AAB73|access-date= 2017-06-11}}</ref>

Based on recent [[DNA phenotyping|DNA-analysis]], the genus ''Ploceus'' is almost certainly [[Polyphyly|polyphyletic]]. If all species currently included in the genus would remain and the genus would be made monophyletic, it would have to encompass the entire subfamily Ploceinae. The Ploceinae can be divided into two groups. In the first group, the widowbirds and bishops (genus ''[[Euplectes]]'') are sister to a clade in which the genera ''[[Foudia]]'' and ''[[Quelea]]'' are closest relatives and which further includes the Asiatic species of ''Ploceus'', i.e. ''[[Ploceus manyar|P. manyar]]'', ''[[Ploceus philippinus|P. philippinus]]'', ''[[Ploceus benghalensis|P. benghalensis]]'', ''[[Ploceus megarhynchus|P. megarhynchus]]'', (and ''[[Ploceus hypoxanthus|P. hypoxanthus]]'', although untested). Since [[Georges Cuvier]] picked ''P. philippinus'' as the [[Type (biology)|type species]], these five species would logically remain assigned to the genus ''Ploceus''.

Basic to the second group is a clade consisting of both species sofar included in ''Ploceus'' that live on Madagascar, ''P. nelicourvi'' and ''[[Ploceus sakalava|P. sakalava]]'', and these are morphologically very distinct from the remaining species. These two species could in future be assigned to the genus ''Nelicurvius'' that was erected by [[Charles Lucien Bonaparte]] in 1850, but which was merged with ''Ploceus'' later on. This second group further contains the genera ''[[Malimbus]]'' and ''[[Anaplectes]]'', and all remaining ''Ploceus'' species.<ref name=Phyl />
